1. Prerequisites
    Install Docker Desktop.
    (Mac Users) Enable VirtioFS in Docker Settings for faster performance.

2. Installation
Bash
git clone https://github.com/lkbrennan97/IMT-542-Transit-Lab.git
cd IMT-542-Transit-Lab
docker compose --profile ingest build

3. Setup Data
Place your GTFS .txt files (e.g., stops.txt) into the data/gtfs/ directory.

Execution Commands:
Map GTFS to RDF
Transform raw CSV data into a Knowledge Graph using the YARRRML mappings.
Bash
docker compose --profile ingest run --rm transformer python -m morph_kgc /app/config/morph_config.ini

Validate Results:
Run SHACL validation against the generated triples.
Bash
docker compose --profile ingest run --rm transformer pyshacl -s data/shapes.ttl output/transit_knowledge_graph.nq

Launch Database (Fuseki):
Start the SPARQL endpoint and access the UI.
Bash
docker compose up -d fuseki
    Dashboard: http://localhost:3030
    Credentials: admin / admin

Project Structure:
    config/: Contains morph_config.ini (engine settings).
    mappings/: Contains stops.yaml (YARRRML mapping logic).
    data/gtfs/: Raw GTFS source files (ignored by Git).
    output/: Generated .nq or .ttl files.

Mac-Specific Notes:
    Platform: Docker is set to linux/amd64 for library compatibility on M-series chips.
    Line Endings: Ensure VS Code is set to LF (not CRLF) to prevent script errors.
    Permissions: Run chmod +x run_ingest.sh if using helper scripts.

Syncing with the Team:
    Pull: git pull origin main to get the latest mapping logic.
    Push: Use a GitHub Personal Access Token (PAT) when prompted for a password.
